<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-188-144 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 513 200</DOCID><JOURNAL>Home Office Computing  April 1991 v9 n4 p50(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The shopper's page. (one of five articles in 'Finding thetechnology that works for you')(includes related article onchoosing a printer)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Chen, Steven C.M.; Stevenson, Edward P.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Buying a computer for a home-based business is costly; however,the price is tax-deductible.andP;  Home-based-business persons shouldbuy the most powerful computer they can afford; if necessary,money may be saved by buying cheaper peripherals.andP;  Buy extra RAM.andO;Shop for RAM, because prices vary wildly.andP;  Buy as much hard-diskmemory as possible, too, because software is always growing morememory hungry.andP;  Buyers of IBM clones should get both 5.25-inch and3.5-inch floppy drives; they can save money by purchasing amonochrome instead of color VGA monitor.andP;  The monitor should havea dot pitch of no greater than 0.31 mm.andP;  Apple Macintosh buyersare advised to shop for third-party peripherals, such as laserprinters and color monitors.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   Apple Macintosh Plus (Microcomputer) (Business use)Intel 80286 (Microprocessor) (Business use).andO;Topic:     Hardware SelectionHome-based businessesMicrocomputers.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>